Re: て+いる　confusion
by Hyperworm » Tue 11.16.2010 6:06 pm I'll use 消える. (消えている means "is gone[disappeared]".)The following are possible ways:消えかけている消えている途中だ消えているところだ消えつつある (fairly formal/literary)I'm slightly shaky on this, so can someone else confirm that these work, and which of these can apply to 行く?(The other, probably less satisfying, answer to your question is: rephrase the sentence so that you don't need to use the progressive form with that verb.)(e.g. instead of "is [presently] going to", use "is headed to[今東京に向かっています]". I think that works...)
